<BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">quote:</font><HR> the only people this would directly hit are those who want to change their enire path to matter. Those people really should play it form the gorupnd up as it is actually an entirely different class in this case, and you woudl want to develop the skills neccessary to be effective at it. Many will only do this to jump on he "LeeT PvPer" bandwagon. most will be happy to allow the new spells to accent the mind spec sorceror they enjoy playing already. <HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>A couplte of points about this:<P>1) I disagree that anything they could add to the matter line could make the sorceror so dramatically different that you'd have to play from level one to get used to it.<P>2) If the classes and lines are truly balanced, sepcializing in matter shouldn't make you "l33t," it should just offer a different play style perhaps.<P>3) For those of us who built our character with the sole intent of RvRing -- and who, in fact, bought the game largely for that reason -- the fact that the matter line could end up as THE definitive RvR line is exactly what makes the possibility of a re-spec absolutely essential.  Moreover, since the end-game is all about RvR, certainly if matter ends up being a strong RvR line people would have chosen that line because it makes sense (unless you wanna go solo MOBs at level 50 while all your friends RvR).  It's not a quest to be "l33t," it's a logical decision -- moreover, it's a decision that those of us who did not select matter are denied of unless we get to re-spec.<P>--------------------<P>--Kestrel Trebor, Sorceror<BR>The Sacred Brotherhood<BR>"Honor, loyalty, and above all, brotherhood!"<BR>Albion, Percival Server
