<IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/daoc/profile_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Profile for Ellejienne"></A> &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://" target=_new><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/daoc/homepage.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Author's Homepage"></A> &nbsp;  &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/daoc/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=edit_post&f=21&t=000282&reply_num=000010&u=00001669"><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/daoc/edit_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Edit/Delete Post"></A> &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/daoc/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=reply&f=21&t=000282&replyto=000010"><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/daoc/quote_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Reply With Quote"></A>
</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#12350C">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
We do have to consider anotehr thing here also. If you are level 36 and have not trained matter since level 1, you will feel cheated. But what happens if you hit level 37? You now have 37 points to spend. this will immediately take you to level 8 in this skill. By next level you can have this almost to level 12. So you CAN get to the 1/2 spec that makes a secondary line useful in only 3 levels. this is not so bad.<P>the only people this would directly hit are those who want to change their enire path to matter. +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<P>Actually this will directly hit me Bullseye. Here is why:<P>I *planned* out my advancement already based on what we knew so as to get key spells at certain levels.<P>At lv35 I am 28 body/20 mind.  I did this to get the 28 specialized mind scream and now I must race mind to 32 (which I will get at lv42, only one level late to charm 41 creatures, something I did not mind losing to get the 28 blast early)<P>The lv28 blast has helped very much in the tough 30s since I am a very good blaster and groups can see what I add.<P>As you can see, it is not so simple as to 'put all in matter from 36 onward'.  Especially since I guessed mind would become more and more important in the 40s so I designed it to peak then. If I did put most into matter I would end up at 50 with a 30/30/30 sorcerer which is not what I want at all.  Not to mention I could not get the matter spells until mid40s (long way off for me) or neglect mind until then (which would make me quite weak in the charm/mez department which I also do not want)<P>So I ask again, is it fair to give one set of rules, then change the rules and not let us adapt to the new rules?<P>Or is it my own fault that I designed my character so intricately?<P>Or is throwing out fully developed characters when abilities change going to be commonplace in Camelot?<P>I think these are vital questions that arise from the way Mythic has designed the skill system, and I imagine they are debating them too.  We are a voice of influence here aren't we? I would not bother writing anything if all I ever was going to hear was 'This is how it is going to be whether its right or wrong'  Seems to me Mythic has gone way out of their way to attend to player input.<P>In any case, thanks for keeping us updated on what the devs are thinking Bullseye.  But jeez I wish I could just play and never have to be constantly guessing how I should spend my hard earned points!
</FONT>
